{"key":"post-10484925","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10484925</id>\n<content>The figure of 100 feet per minute of airspeed is correct.&amp;nbsp; However, for a 4 square foot filter, I'd go a tad over 400 cfm, because we don't live in a perfect world.&amp;nbsp; There is resistance and drag to contend with, and you'll lose a little bit of flow in your prefilter, which is necessary if you want your expensive laminar flow filter to last a long time.&amp;nbsp; I'd look for a blower with around 500 cfm at .9&quot; to 1.1&quot; of static pressure and you'll be much better off.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I wouldn't waste time building anything but a &lt;i&gt;laminar&lt;/i&gt; flow hood with a certified filter.&amp;nbsp; The time and trouble are worth more than the savings on a cheapie that could lead to failure down the road.&amp;nbsp; Don't forget to build a plenum behind the filter at least as large as the filter itself.&amp;nbsp; The plenum is important for achieving laminar flow.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10484982</next>\n<prev>10484777</prev>\n<first>10471855</first>\n<last>10491595</last>\n<when>1244687765</when>\n<utime>06/11/09 05:36 AM</utime>\n</post>"}